article.headline: Oregon's inside men too much for struggling WSU
article.linkText: Ducks impress Cougars with their outside shooting
article.story: PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) -- The Oregon Ducks are no longer a Top 25 team, but they looked the part Thursday night against Washington State. The Ducks shot 58 percent from the field, had 22 assists and made just 12 turnovers in an 89-70 rout. Luke Jackson scored 24 points and Luke Ridnour added 21 points, seven assists and three steals for Oregon (18-6, 8-5 Pacific-10). Jerry McNair had 20 points and Randy Green 18 for the Cougars (5-18, 0-14), who have lost 14 in a row and 21 consecutive Pac-10 games. ''We ran our offense pretty well tonight; we got a lot of people involved,'' said Ridnour, who made all eight of his free throws to extend his school and Pac-10 record to 59. The Ducks pulled away late in the first half to build a 38-29 lead at the break, and WSU never threatened in the second half. Oregon's offensive execution was impressive, featuring crisp passes that led to easy baskets and a good mix of inside and perimeter scoring. ''Their big guys outplayed our big guys,'' WSU coach Paul Graham said. Oregon coach Ernie Kent said his team's young big men have been unfairly criticized this season. Kent noted that Oregon is 17-0 when the Ducks' inside players score 22 or more points. Led by senior Robert Johnson's 12 points, Oregon's inside players combined for 28 points Thursday night. ''Our 'bigs' played well,'' Jackson said. So did Jackson, who had scored a total of 14 points in the previous two games. Jackson, who averages 16, suffered a severe finger cut Jan. 23 against Washington. ''It's been really tough playing with the hurt finger ... tonight, the hand felt a little bit better,'' Jackson said. ''I'm getting more confidence in it.'' The Cougars have matched the 0-14 Pac-10 start of the 1999-2000 Cougars for the worst start to league play in school history. The Cougars shot just 40 percent from the floor and had only six assists; they had 19 turnovers. The Ducks, who play home games at loud and lively McArthur Court, said they found it difficult playing in front of a typically small and quiet WSU crowd of 2,212. ''You've got to create your own energy,'' Ridnour said. ''It's a tough environment to play in,'' Jackson added, ''but we really buckled down and played well for 40 minutes.''
